			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Fantastic work Xalmat!  Here's a few notes/corrections for the tables...
<br />

<br />
DPoC focused Epic pet is <span style="font-weight: bold">277 HP/tic </span>regen.  I'm absolutely sure of it, I have tested it 2 different ways.  DPoC focused Epic pet has<span style="font-weight: bold"> 4300 HP </span>according to the tests I have ran.  Also, be sure to mention DPoC focused Epic pet enrages at 10% just like the PoP pets.  The non focused Damage Sheild of Epic is 50 points (pet level +1) and the DPoC focused Epic pet DS is 51 points (pet level +1).  It's also important to note the extremely high aggro of Epic pet.  Finally Epic pet always runs SoW speed without DPoC focus, and he does NOT run SoW speed with the DPoC focus.
<br />

<br />
Quote from top post:
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Command: /pet attack 
<br />
UI Button: Attack 
<br />
Effect: places the owners current target onto the pet's Hate List, and ends /pet hold. 
<br />
Detail: pet will temporarily forget all prior commands and attempt to attack the target at the top of his hate list. The pet will not forget targets it already hates. It will not "forget" movement states, such as follow or guard, it will just temporarily ignore them as he attempts to attack his target. After the mob dies, the pet will return to his previous guard point, follow, or sit down, as previously commanded. The pet may be sidetracked however if another MOB begins to attack him before he has engagued the target OR if another MOB is doing signifigantly more damage to the pet thus generating enough aggro to make the pet switch targets. 
<br />
Special Note: you may also use the alternative version of this command /pet kill 
<br />
PvP Note: unless Player versus Player is enabled, you cannot add a player or a player charmed NPC to a pet's Hate List. 
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I would slightly change the text here...
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">/pet attack </span>does not place the target at the top of the pets hate list, it just makes the pet attack the mob at the top of his hate list.  There is a difference.  If your pet is fighting a mob for say 20 seconds, then you hit /pet hold he will simply ignore his hate list.  Let's say a friend roots the mob your pet was on and your /pet hold command moves your pet away from that mob.  Now you target a new mob and hit /pet attack.  Your pet will return to the first mob it was fighting and begin fighting again.  This was for the exact reason I stated.  /pet attack simply places the target on your pets hate list and allows the pet to engage in combat again.  But your pet will always engage the mob at the top of his hate list.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
Command: /pet hold 
<br />
Effect: causes the pet to be Held, i.e. it ignores its Hate List and goes into Free mode, resuming its regular movement (either follow, guard, or sit). 
<br />
Detail: this command does not clear the pets hate list, the pet will remain "held" until you give it an attack command at which time it will attempt to attack the target at the top of its hate list. It is recommended you add the following line after /pet hold in a macro: /pet back off to ensure your pets hate list is clear. A pets hate list is frozen while it is "held", which means it does not add anyone or MOB to its hate list even if attacked. 
<br />
Special Note: the command is only available to level 59 or higher Magicians who have obtained the magician class AA skill Pet Discipline at a cost of 6 AA points. 
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
You might avoid extra questions by stating how mages must spend 6 points in General, and 12 points in Archtype along with being level 59 before they can buy this.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
If your pet dies or is reclaimed mid-battle, all damage done by it goes to zero. 
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
The damage is still done, it's just that the damage ownership goes to zero.  Not trying to mix words, but they do have different meanings.  It's also important to note that the pet's owner remains on the hate list, but with very low aggro values.  So a pet dying wipes the pets damage from the damage ownwership table, but not the owner from the hate list.
<br />

<br />
Crimsen asked:
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">how does GoDS effect the pets ability to regen? is it &gt; or &lt; then DPoC? 
<br />

<br />
just wondering which will make the pets a lil nicer.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
In other threads it has been stated...
<br />
Earth pet 
<br />
Unfocused - 79 max hit, 4800 hp, regens 2% hp per tick (96/tic)
<br />
Gloves - 82 max hit, 5500 hp, regens 1.75% hp per tick (96/tic)
<br />
Symbol - 90 max hit, 6200 hp, regens 3% per tick (186/tic)
<br />

<br />
and from my own testing I know
<br />
DPoC - 81 max hit, 5250 hp, ~5.1% hp per tick (270/tic)
<br />

<br />
So if all these values are correct, it appears the best HP regen for PoP pets is ASoS, then DPoC.  GoDS seems to not add HP regen.  This is assuming the numbers given elsewhere for % regen and HP for GoDS are correct.
<br />

<br />
